# StarCI Academy Design Patterns

## 1) Redux Pattern

- Use Redux Toolkit `createSlice` with a tiny, explicit state shape per domain (`tabs`, `course`, `module`, `sidebar`, ...).
- Keep slice actions focused on one intent (e.g. `setSidebar`, `setLearnTab`, `setCourseDisplayId`), avoid overloaded actions.
- Prefer enum-based UI state for tabs/modes (`LearnTab`, `SidebarTab`) instead of string literals spread across components.
- Store identifiers in Redux (`displayId`, `id`) and derive fetched entities via SWR hooks.
- `store.ts` is the single reducer registry; when adding a slice:
  1) export reducer/actions in `src/redux/slices/*`
  2) re-export from `src/redux/slices/index.ts`
  3) register reducer in `src/redux/store.ts`.
- Keep serializable values in Redux; if non-serializable is unavoidable, document why near state/action.

## 2) Effect Hook Pattern (`src/hooks/effects`)

- `UseEffects.tsx` is the composition root for global sync effects; add new cross-cutting effects there.
- Effect hooks should do one sync responsibility:
  - URL/params -> Redux (`useSyncReduxCourseId`, `useSyncReduxModuleId`)
  - Redux <-> query string (`useSetTabQuery`)
  - Redux -> navigation (`useSidebar`)
- Guard early inside effects (`if (!courseDisplayId) return`, route scope checks, same-path checks) to avoid infinite redirects and noisy rerenders.
- Depend on stable primitives and state used in the effect body; avoid hidden dependencies.
- Keep these hooks side-effect only (no UI return, no view logic).

## 3) Data Fetching Pattern (SWR + Redux)

- Query hooks (`useQuery*Swr`) fetch remote data and then hydrate Redux with normalized/current entity.
- SWR key should be `null` when required identifiers are missing.
- Throw explicit errors for missing required params or missing response payload.
- Components read from Redux for rendering; hooks own fetching and cache semantics.

## 3.1) Singleton Formik Pattern (`src/hooks/singleton/formik`)

- Keep Formik logic in singleton hooks, not directly inside page components.
- Structure for each form:
  - `core/useXxxFormik.ts`: owns `initialValues`, `validationSchema`, `onSubmit`.
  - `impls/useXxxFormik.ts`: returns formik instance via `FormikContext`.
  - register in `FormikContext.tsx` and provider value.
  - export via `core/index.ts` + `impls/index.ts` + `formik/index.ts`.
- UI components/pages only consume singleton hooks (e.g. `useCvApplyFormik`) and bind HeroUI fields to Formik state.
- Validation messages should use i18n message keys; map keys to translated text in UI with `t(...)`.

## 3.2) Singleton Modal Overlay Pattern (`src/hooks/singleton/overlay-state` + `src/components/modals`)

- Keep modal open/close state in singleton overlay hooks, not as local page state when the modal is part of global app UX.
- Structure for each overlay:
  - `core/useXxxOverlayState.ts`: returns `useOverlayState()`.
  - `impls/useXxxOverlayState.ts`: maps context state to `{ isOpen, onOpen, onClose, onOpenChange }`.
  - register in `OverlayStateContext.tsx` and provider value.
  - export via `core/index.ts`, `impls/index.ts`, and `overlay-state/index.ts`.
- Put modal UI under `src/components/modals/XxxModal/index.tsx` and mount in `ModalContainer`.
- Pages/components should call singleton overlay hooks (e.g. `onOpen`) instead of rendering modal markup inline.

## 4) Routing Pattern (`pathConfig`)

- Build routes through `pathConfig()` only; avoid hardcoding path strings in components/hooks.
- Nested route builders should mirror folder structure under `src/app`.
- For learn flows, route builders stay under `.course(displayId).learn()` (e.g. `mindMap`, `module`, `cv`, `finalProject`, `leaderboard`).
- When adding a new learn subsection, add builder method in `pathConfig` before wiring UI navigation.

## 5) Component Composition Pattern

- Route files in `src/app/**` stay thin; put UI and behavior in `src/components/**` or route-local component folders when strongly scoped.
- Split complex UI into focused components:
  - Container/state orchestration in parent (`Sidebar/index.tsx`)
  - Reusable presentational branch in child (`Sidebar/Accordion/index.tsx`)
- Pass explicit props for selected state and callbacks (`selected`, `extraId`, `onSelectSubItem`) instead of reading global state deep in child trees.
- Derive render lists with `useMemo` when based on Redux/entity data and reused in render maps.

## 6) Sidebar Interaction Pattern (Current Learn Module)

- Sidebar dispatches `setSidebar({ tab, extraId? })` on selection.
- Parent item click sets `tab` and clears `extraId` when needed.
- Accordion child click sets both `tab` and `extraId`.
- Highlight rules:
  - top-level item active by `sidebar.tab`
  - accordion parent active only when `tab` matches and `extraId` is empty
  - accordion child active when child key equals `extraId`.
- Navigation side effect is centralized in `useSidebar`, not inside rendering components.

## 7) Styling and Layout Pattern

- Prefer Tailwind utility classes colocated with component markup.
- Use HeroUI state data attributes for active styles (e.g. `data-[selected=true]:text-accent`) when available.
- Keep sticky/scroll behavior owned by layout wrappers (grid/columns), while inner components only manage local scroll sections.

## 8) Implementation Checklist (for new feature)

- Add/extend Redux slice if UI state must be shared.
- Add route builder(s) in `pathConfig` first.
- Add/update effect hook if syncing Redux with router/query is required.
- Keep page thin; move UI and logic into components/hooks.
- Wire selected state + callbacks explicitly across component boundaries.
- Run lints after edits and fix all introduced diagnostics.
